---
import ProjectLayout from '../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
import YouTube from '../components/YouTube.astro';
import Gallery from '../components/Gallery.astro';

const images = [
  { src: '/images/TypicalSection3D/typical-section-3d-screenshot-01.png' },
  { src: '/images/TypicalSection3D/typical-section-3d-screenshot-02.png' },
  { src: '/images/TypicalSection3D/typical-section-3d-screenshot-03.png' },
  { src: '/images/TypicalSection3D/typical-section-3d-screenshot-04.png' },
  { src: '/images/TypicalSection3D/typical-section-3d-screenshot-05.png' },
  { src: '/images/TypicalSection3D/typical-section-3d-screenshot-06.png' },
];
---

<ProjectLayout title="3D Typical Section Creator">
  <YouTube id="bNnHhnhOzIc" />

  <h2>Screenshots</h2>
  <Gallery images={images} />

  <h2>Project description</h2>
  <p><strong>What are typical sections?</strong></p>
  <p>
    A "section" is shortened way of saying "cross-section view", a type of 2D non-perspectival drawing
    commonly used in engineering and architecture to show what something looks like when you take a slice
    of it and look at it head-on.
  </p>
  <p>
    Similarly, a street section is a cross section view of a street, showing the widths and placement of
    vehicle lanes, bike lanes, sidewalks, trees, street furniture or accessories (like benches or street lamps),
    as well as engineering information like how the road is sloped to facilitate drainage, or the locations of
    underground utilities.
  </p>
  <p>
    Although sections can be simplified line drawings, urban designers and landscape architects have created
    very colorful illustrative street sections, removing most of the engineering particulars to communicate
    how a street could be designed to feel safe, walkable or habitable.
  </p>
  <p>
    This application is the 3D version of <a href="https://streetmix.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Street Mix</a>
  </p>
</ProjectLayout>
